<text>5/5/21 I'm completely editing my previous review as EVERYONE is entitled to bad days and so many variations of events may have occurred such as new staff or perhaps understaffed that day. We have eaten there so many times since that initial post, Hog Canyon deserves an updated & current review of their establishment. Hog Canyon has the best and juiciest Bacon, Cheeseburgers in Yolo County. Their fries are fantastic! fresh, hot, huge portions that you are left so stuffed with great prices They have great pizza we especially enjoy their combinaions. Our grandkids LOVE the Canadian Pizza. Their crust is very good. Homemade huge salads are very filling. Do NOT Miss their Tri-Tip sandwiches which are packed with excellently cooked Tri-Tip roast cooked over a great oak wood heat source can be smelled a mile away from the beginning of town at the signal light. Which light? THE ONLY LIGHT!!! *lol* Honestly folks I have no horse in this race! They truly have great food and you will NOT be disappointed. After eating here, you'll never want to eat at a fast food joint again!! Their staff are friendly, aim to please and make sure you're their priority and truly believe in customer satisfaction. Oh ya, the milkshakes are bomb, as well as, their homemade cookies. They always sell out of cookies. Thank You Hog Cyn for serving our wonderful little community with excellence.</text>< pics>

<name>Benjamin Spitler</name><Resp>{'time': 1565508418631, 'text': 'I am glad we were able to get it resolved.'}< /Resp>< Text>
UPDATE - 7/18/19:
I was contacted by one of the owners after posting my review and was very impressed by his concern and understanding. He assured me that all my concerns have been corrected or are in the process of being corrected. He also promised to make up for the damaged rear window defrost lines. He fulfilled this promise by paying for the replacement of the rear window. I am very pleased with my interactions with the owner and have added a star to my review. I truly wish my entire experience was as pleasant as this. Unfortunately, I'm still just at square one and had to deal with these issues over the past month. I hope that they do indeed learn from this experience and improve overall as a business.

-------------------------------------------------

I'm very disappointed in the work done by this shop as well as the overall lack of professionalism.

To begin, I was referred to superior window tint by a local dealer for tinting my brand new '19 GTI. At first it seemed smooth; I made an appointment online, dropped of my car, and came back 3 hours later to a tinted car. When I looked over the car, the work seemed pretty good except for 2 small windows in front of the driver door. They had tint but were totally  bubbled because they said they couldn't get their hands in the tight space. I googled the issue and right off the bat found videos showing how to do these properly. They told me the bubbles would clear up after the moisture evaporated and to give it a couple days.

A week later, the small windows were still completely bubbled, the edges of the rear window were all peeling up, and all other windows had bubbles around the top edges. I scheduled another appointment and returned to the shop and explained the issues. They reluctantly took the car in and I returned in 3 hours to a completely re-tinted car. Unfortunately the small front windows still looked terrible, but instead of bubbles there were squeegee streaks all over them. I was again assured the streaks would clear up when the moisture evaporated so I went on my way.

Another week goes by and all windows have tiny dust particle bubbles all over them. And of course the tiny windows still look terrible. I was pretty frustrated at this point because I had paid over $400 for the tint work and I've never had any of these issues before. I made an appointment and went back in. I was meet with a serious attitude from what I assume to be the owner. I showed him the problem areas and told him I wanted them to remove the tint and issue a refund since I couldn't trust them to do it properly. They took the car in and I waited for them to remove the tint. As I was waiting, the owner didn't say a single word to me and I only know I received a refund because I got an email receipt while he was sitting at the desk. Not one word from him. When they were done removing the tint the guy pulled it out, handed me the keys, and the owner was nowhere to be seen so I left.

After getting home I realized they also did a terrible job removing the tint (probably because they were frustrated and I wasn't paying to have it removed so they had no incentive to do a good job). There was still adhesive all around the edges of all the windows, they left gobs of adhesive all over the inside trim off my car, they left a razor blade in my trunk, they scratched up my window trim, and they damaged my defogger lines on my back window in about 20 places with the razor blade.

Overall the manager was very unprofessional, the workers seemed to not be trained properly, and I'm much worse of than when I started thanks to wasted Saturdays, wasted gas, and the damage they did to my car.

DO NOT TAKE YOUR CAR HERE. Go literally anywhere else.</Text>

< rating>
4</rating>
<review>I can only review the happy hour. First $2 beers is a steal. The outside is gorgeous because it offers a great view of the ocean. The inside is nice, although it is very dimly lit so keep that in mind.

The food is alright for what you pay for, nothing spectacular, but for the happy hour prices it's darn good deal. The spicy calamari is my favorite along side the miso soup.

Desert is also wonderful, their mochi balls are beautifully plated and the churros with ice cream are equally delectable.

I couldn't give it 5 stars because I had the house fried rice with chicken and it was pretty medicore for a $12 dollar dish. The rice was very oily and it didn't offer much to distinguish itself.<//review><Pictures>None</Pictures><Resp>None< /Resp>< gmapID>

< Review>
We've been coming here pretty consistently for the last 5 years and I have to say that the hospitality has always been quite ok......until this afternoon.

We came in around 4:30-4:45-ish (GM/Bossman, take note of the shift; May 17th, 2014) and requested for a table in the patio with the hostess upfront. She said it'll be a 45 min wait, so sure, we were fine with that. We asked to be seated first and have maybe a small appetizer while we wait (simply an edamame, etc.) for the table outside to open up. Right away, she said "That'll be a little difficult to do..."

Ok, in that case, "we want to sit at the bar and have a couple sakes and beers while we wait..." She was hesitant and didn't even give us an answer but grabbed the menus to get us seated and immediately you can tell she had a bit of an attitude and gave off a bad vibe. Woman, you're working in the restaurant industry, when you're pissed off, don't show it on your face (develop your EQ, please)!

And to make things worse, she dogged us numerous times while we were dining (and even when I was walking to the washroom). Seriously? Is this the type of hostess you want for your restaurant, Sushi On The Rock??

The rest of the servers were quite friendly and very hospitable. And they were willing to cater to us unconditionally (c'mon, we weren't even asking much).

Please reevaluate your hostess (remember, 4:30-4:45pm on Saturday, May 17th, 2014). I'm sure many other customers would appreciate this as well.< /Review>

< review>
Do not buy a car from this dealer unless you live within a few miles of the dealership.

I have never experienced such terrible customer service.. the shocker is that they are a BMW dealer so we expected so much more. What a disappointment.

To start with we were out of state buyers. They do not like out of state buyers because apparently it is too much work. We were very surprised - as was BMW USA. We have purchased cars from out of state before and even shipped a car from Hawaii and never had any issues.

My Dad worked a car dealership for over 30 years. Every customer had value and out of state buyers were a large part of their business. Considering BMW does not have a presence in smaller communities, selling cars to people who are not local shouldn't be a new thing; it seems a bit discriminatory as well.

They FINALLY agreed to sell us the car....after weeks of hassle. Then we could not get them to send any paperwork or the shipping information.
We asked, and asked - to no avail. They requested and received our cashier's check - issued directly from the banks account. Cashier's checks are equal to cash where I am from, but this was like the Twilight Zone because they held up the deal for another 10 days while the check "cleared their account."

They also refused to sell us the car if there was a lienholder...apparently it was too much paperwork. Cash deals only if you live out of state.

Still no paperwork, no shipping information...no car. At this point we were six weeks into this all-consuming hassle. We tried to remain friendly and professional , but things had gotten really ridiculous.
Request after request for shipping information only to be told they were working on it. Their constant excuse for the lack of timeliness? "That is why we don't sell to out of state buyers."

Absolutely shocking.

I noticed that they like to discredit people who post bad reviews so for the record:
My daughter was the person trying to purchase this car, Riverside BMW agree to sell it to her and happily took her money.......this is called a CONTRACT.

This is a legitimate review - I generally do not write bad reviews because it is unfortunate that people always choose to complain and not compliment. This business has not earned the one star that I gave them - I wish I could give them zero stars but unfortunately that is not possible.

...The car finally showed up last Thursday....approximately 2 months after her first conversation with the dealer.< /review>

< text>
Soooo.... I had a reading of a right brake light malfunction on my beloved BMW 435i, aka, the Weekend Whip. Fabian Hernandez was assigned as my Aftersales Consultant.

Mr. Hernandez was probably the absolute best representative of any car maintenance situation I have ever encountered. "How do you mean?‚Äù you ask. For me, going to the dealership, any dealership for ANY reason brings me a dark shade of red-zoned anxiety. Note that this is my third BMW. Also note that it's the car, not the people, that keep me laced in the comforts of these ultimate driving machines. This day was different. For starters, Mr. Hernandez was respectful, smiled (seems to be a lost art), explained then confirmed that I understood what he shared without being condescending or rushed (and away went round one of my anxiety). His follow-up was very commendable as well (the Weekend Whip stayed overnight) - pleasant, detailed voice mail and texts to keep me updated on the progress of the repair. Now, you may be thinking, "That's what an Aftersales Consultant is *supposed* to do". Yeah, but many of you know that is definitely not always the case.

My Sweetie, who drives something comparably a few pegs below interesting, came along and let me know throughout the appointment that the level of service and attention far exceeded his expectations. He was right.

The second round of my anxiety was dismissed when Mr. Hernandez shared the good and great news that the warranty covered my repair. Something out of his control of influence, but I give him credit for being the messenger.

A shout out to BMW of Riverside. Thank you for good and great service.

~Dr. Gina M. Newton
& her beloved BMW 435i (aka, the Weekend Whip)</text>

<Rating>1<//Rating>< review>
I leased a 2020 BMW 330i from BMW of Riverside, which was a previous loaner vehicle. I went through a car broker to lease this vehicle and the vehicle was delivered to my home in Sylmar, CA, by a dealer staff (~80 miles). I was very excited when I received the vehicle and so to my disadvantage, I did not do a thorough inspection before signing my paperwork, and being a workday, I only took it around the block (<0.5 mile) and immediately parked it in my garage.

The following day I had a better look at the vehicle, inside and out, and noted a few faults. 1) The windshield had a crack; 2) there was hot glue-like stains in the center console area (3 specific areas ‚Äì including the shift knob); 3) a speaker sounded busted; 4) both front wheels had curb damage but were repaired by the dealer (poorly).

I reached out to the broker and asked about issues 1, 2, and 3. He said he will get in touch with the dealer. BMW of Riverside told my broker to take the vehicle in to inspect the issues. I scheduled an appointment and took the vehicle in. The dealer fixed the speaker issue (3) under warranty and said if I wanted the windshield (1) and console stains (2) fixed, it would be charged to me at a price of $2,500 and $1,600, respectively. They are trying to put these damages on me stating it passed inspection before being delivered to me.

To note, I saw two dealer employees inspect my vehicle before accepting it in for service and neither noted the issues until I pointed them out. I am not saying that staff is incompetent, but I noted that they are not thorough.

I am very disappointed how this dealer has and is treating a loyal customer by blaming their mistakes on me and will never shop at BMW of Riverside again and will encourage all of my friends and family the same.</review>

BMW of Riverside - What can I say? A lot!

BMW of Riverside - hands down, is a dealership and service center that definitely outshines the five star rating system. The customer service provided by the associates was by far the best I have ever received. Everyone I interacted with at BMW of Riverside was warm and welcoming, helpful and attentive, efficient and effective, professional and knowledgeable, courteous and empathetic - not to mention they were all some of the best looking representatives I have ever had the opportunity and pleasure to do business with. The service center, showroom, and lobby were all very well maintained and provided an excellent atmosphere and relaxing setting.

And that was all very much appreciated.  I had been sitting in my car in freezing cold weather and in the fog after running over some rocks that caused a lot of undercarriage damage to my vehicle. Alone, I waited for a tow truck to come up the mountain, almost six hours, and once one finally showed up, I felt like there was going to be more disaster and disappointment ahead.

I couldn‚Äôt have been more wrong! I was amazed at how quickly I was assisted at BMW of Riverside, and I was on my way home in less than an hour!

I arrived to the service center in a tow truck and tears and left in a brand new BMW 330i loaner with a smile on my face and feeling confident that everything would work out for the best.

And it did! Even though I hadn‚Äôt heard from my insurance company‚Äôs adjuster, I did receive a call from BMW of Riverside. They didn‚Äôt have an answer as to whether my insurance company would pay to have my car fixed or claim it as a total loss (which was not their fault, but due to a rescheduling made by the insurance company‚Äôs adjuster) but they still graciously allowed me to continue using the loaner car.

Fast forward two weeks (approximate) I returned the loaner and picked up my car which was ready, all due to the collaborative effort put forth between BMW of Riverside and StateFarm Insurance Company. I am happy to say that my car was completely repaired by professional BMW mechanics and to what I believe better condition than before!

Thank you BMW of Riverside!<//review>

<Text>Fool me once, shame on you; fool me twice, shame on me. Fool me three times:
It all started a year and a half ago when I first brought in my 2015 328xi Gran Turismo for service at BMW of Riverside. I went in for a change in brake fluid after receiving notification on my vehicle, and after the service was performed, the BMW Riverside Service Department would not release me my vehicle. I was told ‚Äúmy brakes were too low to release me the vehicle‚Äù, and that an $1,100 brake rotor and pad service would need to be performed. I declined, as the price quoted is more than what I was given elsewhere such as Sterling and Crevier and wanted the service performed either of these locations; they held my vehicle hostage and would not release me my vehicle, even though I had driven it there in the first place. A week goes by as I plead with the Service Department to release me MY property, with no give. I cave, as I needed my vehicle for work, and have the vehicle towed elsewhere at my expense. Strike one for withholding my personal possessions that weren‚Äôt even initially purchased at this location.

A couple months go by, and my vehicle starts exhibiting strange behavior. I would receive the dreaded infamous ‚ÄúDrivetrain Malfunction‚Äù notification on my vehicle‚Äôs screen, and the vehicle would go into ‚Äúlimp mode‚Äù with full engine output not available. Turning the car off and on would temporarily reset the vehicle back to normal, until the issue would reappear a few hundred miles later. Foolishly after the first incident with this dealership, I take my car back for service at BMW Riverside being that is the slightly-closest location. I, like many this day and age, have an OBD II reader and a companion app that can read BMW diagnostic and error codes that are shown to the dealer when they check on your vehicle. The error codes stored in the vehicle stated that cylinders 2 and 4 were shutting down due to not receiving enough fuel: a mechanical malfunction. I have an extended warranty on my vehicle that covers the full cost of repair for all mechanical faults around engine components with a small deductible. I mention this mechanical fault to the service representative when first dropping off my vehicle for service; I sign for the diagnostic thinking, when I get my vehicle serviced it‚Äôll go towards the repair cost anyway. After diagnosing the vehicle, the service rep states that there are NO MECHANICAL FAULTS with the vehicle, and that a software update to the cars ECU would alleviate the issue. I contest him, as the codes stored in the car state that a mechanical fault is present. Beyond that, when the vehicle goes in this limp state, you can physically feel the cars vibrations as the cylinders shut down, and can hear the fuel pump malfunctioning. The Service Manager at the time, Travis,  was very firm in keeping the diagnosis as a software issue in order to avoid having my warranty cover the cost of the repair, and instead wanted to force me to pay out of pocket by misdiagnosing the issue as electronic-related. The service rep once again holds my vehicle hostage until I pay $200 for an incorrect diagnosis; seeing it as a lost cause to contend any further, I pay the full $500 for the diagnosis and ECU update in the hopes that it will fix my issue. Fast forward 2 weeks after I pay for the ECU update, and my vehicle once again goes into limp mode as I‚Äôm commuting to work on the freeway, with the same ‚ÄúDrivetrain Malfunction‚Äù error present.. This time turning the vehicle off and on wouldn‚Äôt return it to normal,  and the vehicle needed to be towed to BMW Riverside, once again at my expense. This time, the service manager Travis acknowledge his mistake, and replaced the low fuel pump on my vehicle to actually fix the issue for no more than the $500 I had already paid. Ultimately, this situation cost me $400 more than it should have as it was a warranty-covered issue, plus the cost of tows and work missed. But it doesn‚Äôt end there: I dropped off my vehicle to BMW Riverside -I have oil dripping from underneath my car.<//Text>< Pictures>

<review>Beware of  deceptive add-ons when purchasing your car.  My wife purchased the maintenance package when she purchased her  car and it was quite expensive for a short period of time.  That says something in itself if you tell me, for a low mileage car.  A couple of weeks later, she decided she did not want it and went to get her money back and was informed no refunds. She did not pursue it any further until about a year later when she was tired of taking it in for maintenance even though she rarely drove it. I went in for regular scheduled maintenance on my 328i (brake fluid, and oil gasket housing had a leak, all covered by warranty, i only paid a small deductible of $50 to replace it). Nick Cappellano was my service advisor and was very helpful, and alwats is every time I come in. He told me that my extendsed warranty was going to expire in just 6 months, so he went ahead and gave me an annual oil change just because he was worried that I wouldnt be able to get one later if my warranty expired. He also offered to help me look for third party warranty companies that will extend the warranty once it expires. When my car was ready for pickup, i came in to swap cars, and as I was walking out to my car, Nick caught up to me to tell me that he filled up my gas tank. I was super happy and wasnt even expecting it. They turned a small little gas issue into a remarkable experience overall. This really is a one of a kind service department and they bend backwards to make sure you leave happy. If any of my family or friends want to buy a BMW someday I'm going to make sure they come to this dealership, and no where else. I'm very lucky to have bought my car from here because they really take good care of me...and my car.<//text>
